{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625395"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17020"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17020"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0.87,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70533"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17020"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55997"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5444"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70533"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immune system has evolved mechanisms to remember previous pathogen encounters, allowing for enhanced responses to subsequent exposures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic feature of acquired immunity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Responds with equal speed to all exposures","Produces only IgM antibodies upon re-exposure","Generates pathogen-specific memory cells that persist long-term","Requires continuous antigen presence to maintain protection","Provides immediate protection against all pathogens"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hallmark of acquired immunity is the generation of \u003Cstrong\u003Epathogen-specific memory cells that persist long-term\u003C/strong\u003E. These memory B and T cells allow for a faster and stronger immune response upon subsequent exposure to the same pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResponds with equal speed to all exposures\u003C/strong\u003E - Secondary immune responses are significantly faster than primary responses due to the presence of memory cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces only IgM antibodies upon re-exposure\u003C/strong\u003E - The secondary immune response predominantly produces IgG antibodies, which provide more effective and targeted protection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires continuous antigen presence to maintain protection\u003C/strong\u003E - Memory cells can persist and maintain protection for years or decades after the initial exposure, even in the absence of antigen.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvides immediate protection against all pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E - Acquired immunity is pathogen-specific and takes time to develop, whereas immediate protection is a characteristic of innate immunity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis system of immunological memory forms the basis for vaccination and provides long-lasting protection against previously encountered pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acquired immunity develops after exposure to pathogens or vaccines through the production of memory B and T cells.","The primary immune response is slower and produces mainly IgM antibodies, while the secondary response is faster and produces mainly IgG antibodies.","Memory cells persist for years or decades, providing long-term protection against specific pathogens."],"references":["Medina KL. Overview of the immune system. Handb Clin Neurol. 2016;133:61-76. doi:10.1016/B978-0-444-63432-0.00004-9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55997"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17020"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55997"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:05:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T19:06:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0